        <div class="container px-5 mx-auto pt-8">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold">Complexity Levels</h3>
            <div class="complexity-bar text-center my-4 pb-3 rounded-lg">
                <div class="complexity-bar-inner flex justify-content leading-tight">
                    <div class="flex-1 mr-1 bg-white bg-opacity-85 rounded-tl-lg py-2">
                        <span class="font-bold text-xl">Low</span><br />1 &dash; 4
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex-1 mr-1 bg-white bg-opacity-85 py-2">
                        <span class="font-bold text-xl">Moderate</span><br />5 &dash; 7
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex-1 mr-1 bg-white bg-opacity-85 py-2">
                        <span class="font-bold text-xl">High</span><br />8 &dash; 10
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex-1 bg-white bg-opacity-85 rounded-tr-lg py-2">
                        <span class="font-bold text-xl">Very High</span><br />> 10
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl pt-6 font-bold">Cyclomatic Complexity</h3>
            <p class="my-4">
                Cyclomatic complexity is computed using the control flow graph of the program: the nodes of the graph
                correspond to indivisible groups of commands of a program, and a directed edge connects two nodes if
                the second command might be executed immediately after the first command. Cyclomatic complexity may
                also be applied to individual functions, modules, methods or classes within a program.
                <a class="underline" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclomatic_complexity" target="_blank">See Wikipedia for more</a>
            </p>
            <p>
                To measure or enforce cyclomatic complexity limits in your application see
